Metal ion implantation into ceramics has been shown to be a reliable technique for tailoring the electrical conductivity of the ceramic piece, and this approach has been applied in various applications. However, a concern with this method is the long-term stability of the implantation-induced conductivity, particularly if the implanted metal species readily oxidizes. Here, we investigate the long-term behavior of the surface conductivity of titanium-implanted alumina. Our results indicate that the conductivity decreases by about 10% over the first year after implantation, with an initial drop of up to 40% in the early stages.

We propose a novel Skyrme-like conserved current in the effective theory of pions and vector mesons, based on the idea of hidden local symmetry. The associated charge is equivalent to the Skyrmion charge for any smooth configuration. Additionally, singular configurations can be identified as $n_f=1$ baryons charged under the new symmetry. Under this identification, vector mesons play the role of Chern-Simons vector fields on the quantum Hall droplet that forms the $n_f=1$ baryon. We suggest that this current is the correct effective expression for the baryon current at low energies, providing a unified picture for the two types of baryons and allowing them to continuously transform into each other in a natural way. Furthermore, Chern-Simons dualities on the droplet can be interpreted as a Seiberg-like duality between gluons and vector mesons.

Continuous-time quantum walks have proven a valuable tool for designing quantum algorithms. In this article, we improve upper bounds for the quantum hitting time, which is the time required for the walk to find a vertex with high probability. Specifically, we apply our techniques to the glued-trees problem, reducing the hitting time bound from $n^5$ to $n^2\log n$. Additionally, our methods improve the dependence on precision of the continuous-time quantum walk algorithm for finding a marked node on an ergodic, reversible Markov chain, from $n^c$ to $e^{c\log n}$.

Extreme mass ratio inspirals (EMRIs) can be classified as dry or wet based on formation mechanisms. Dry EMRIs, previously thought to be the main source for the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna, are produced by multi-body scattering in the nuclear star cluster and gravitational capture. We highlight an alternative channel: wet EMRIs formed with the assistance of the accretion flow around accreting galactic-center massive black holes (MBHs). In this channel, the accretion disk captures stellar-mass black holes on inclined orbits and drives them towards the MBH, boosting the formation rate of EMRIs in such galaxies by orders of magnitude.

When a new user signs up on a website, we typically have no information about him/her, i.e., no interaction with items, no user profile, and no social links with other users. Despite this lack of information, we still expect our recommender systems to attract the users at the first time and encourage them to stay on the website and become active users. This problem falls into the new user cold-start category, which is crucial to the development and survival of a company. Existing works on user cold-start recommendation either require additional user efforts, such as setting up an interview process, or utilize side information [10] like user demographics, locations, social relations, etc. However, users may not be willing to invest the time and effort required for the interview and side information may not be available for cold-start users.

Deep learning has solved problems unreachable by heuristic algorithms. It has been applied to wireless communications, despite well-understood radio systems and optimal algorithms for many tasks. While gains have been obtained by learning individual receiver parts, a better approach is to jointly learn the whole receiver. However, this often results in a challenging nonlinear problem, making the optimal solution infeasible. To address this, we propose deeprx, a deep fully convolutional neural network that executes the receiver pipeline from frequency domain signal stream to uncoded bits in a 5G-compliant manner. We improve channel estimation by constructing the input in a specific manner using both data and pilot symbols.

Mutation-based fuzzing often relies on an initial set of non-crashing seed inputs (corpus) for generating new inputs through mutation. However, this lack of diversity can lead to wasted effort. To address this, fuzzers use distillation tools (e.g., afl-cmin) to select the smallest subset of seeds that triggers the same instrumentation data points as the full corpus. We systematically explore the impact of minimizing the number and cumulative size of seeds on fuzzing efficiency and findings in real-world software.

In this paper, we explore the concept of multi-agent systems with partial observation. We examine how agents can be grouped into different categories based on their similarities in state transition structures, and how a scalable supervisor can be designed using a template that is independent of the number of agents in the system. The scalable supervisor is able to handle the case of partial observation without requiring a complete recomputation, making it more efficient and scalable. We present sufficient conditions for safety and maximal permissiveness of the scalable least restrictive supervisor on the template level, and provide an example to illustrate the proposed approach. This work contributes to the field of multi-agent systems by providing a more efficient and scalable solution for supervisory control in partial observation scenarios.

Electric network frequency (ENF) fluctuations are a valuable tool in multimedia forensics. Our proposed approach uses temporal windowing with a filter-bank capon spectral estimator, followed by a Gohberg-Semencul factorization of the model covariance matrix. Unlike previous methods, we employ a non-rectangular temporal window and utilize Krylov matrices for efficient implementation. Our approach outperforms state-of-the-art methods in ENF estimation, particularly when a short time window of 1 second is used in power recordings.

The direpack package offers a unified set of modern statistical dimension reduction techniques as a single, streamlined package. It groups these methods into three categories: projection pursuit-based dimension reduction, sufficient dimension reduction, and robust m estimators for dimension reduction. Correspondingly, regularized regression estimators based on these reduced dimension spaces are provided, ranging from principal component regression to sparse partial robust m regression. The package also includes a suite of classical and robust preprocessing utilities, such as generalized spatial signs, as well as dedicated plotting tools and cross-validation utilities. Additionally, direpack adheres to the scikit-learn API, allowing seamless integration with (statistical and/or machine) learning pipelines.

The use of high-power laser excitation has enabled the acquisition of high-resolution images with improved spatial resolution. The nonlinearity of the fluorescence emission was used to increase the spatial frequency of the fluorescence image. By modulating the excitation laser's power, the spatial resolution of imaging was improved by approximately 1.6 times in comparison with confocal microscopy.
 The simplicity of the experimental setup and data processing also makes it possible to apply this method for improving the spatial resolution of sensing and biological labeling with the defects in solids.

The paper proposes a Bayesian approach to estimate hyperparameters of a random effects model when there are multiple random effects and the standard frequentist approach using individual survey weights is not applicable. The authors argue that the Bayesian approach is more accurate and consistent than frequentist methods, which rely on numerical integration, as it produces unbiased inference for both the sampling distribution and the population-level distribution. The authors present a weight-exponentiated formulation for the random effects distribution that achieves unbiased inference and contrast their approach with frequentist methods through simulations and a real-data example. The results show that the Bayesian approach outperforms frequentist methods in both unbiasedness and consistency across different modeling formulations and sampling designs. The paper provides a capstone for recent developments in combining traditional survey estimation approaches with Bayesian modeling and bridges the gap between the two subfields.

Low-symmetry 2D materials---such as res$^2$, rese$^2$, black phosphorus, group-IV monochalcogenides, and others---exhibit complex atomic structures compared to honeycomb lattices of graphene, hexagonal boron nitride, and transition metal dichalcogenides. These reduced symmetries lead to inhomogeneous electron, optical, valley, and spin responses, as well as novel properties like ferroelasticity, ferroelectricity, magnetism, spin-wave phenomena, large nonlinear optical properties, photogalvanic effects, and superconductivity. The "beyond graphene: low-symmetry and anisotropic 2D materials" special topic highlights recent experimental and theoretical research on these emerging materials.

This paper shows that the eccentric debris rings around stars Fomalhaut and HD 202628 are narrower than expected in the standard eccentric planet perturbation scenario, sometimes referred to as "pericenter glow." The standard scenario posits initially circular and narrow belts of planetesimals at semi-major axis $a$, whose eccentricity is increased to $e_f$ after gas disc dispersal by secular perturbations from an eccentric planet, resulting in a belt of width $2ae_f$. In a minor modification of this scenario, narrower belts can arise if the planetesimals are initially eccentric, which could result from earlier planet perturbations during the gas-rich protoplanetary disc phase. Alternatively, a primordial eccentricity could be caused by instabilities that increase the disc eccentricity without the need for any planets.

Context. The assembly history of the Milky Way is currently being unveiled thanks to the data provided by the $Gaia$ mission. It is likely that the globular cluster system of our galaxy has followed a similarly intricate formation path. $Aims. To constrain this formation path, we explore the link between the globular clusters and the known merging events that the Milky Way has experienced. $Methods. To this end, we combined the kinematic information provided by $Gaia$ for almost all galactic clusters, with the largest sample of cluster ages available after carefully correcting for systematic errors. To identify clusters with a common origin, we analyzed their dynamical properties, particularly in the space of integrals of motion. $Results. We find that about 40% of the clusters likely formed in situ.

The estimation of a dataset's intrinsic dimension is crucial for dimensionality reduction techniques. This article introduces 'intrinsic', an r package with novel likelihood-based estimators. The package includes three models: two-nn, gride, and hidalgo. High-level functions provide easy access to these efficient, low-level routines. Intrinsic covers homogeneous and heterogeneous dimension estimators, with frequentist and bayesian inference for the first category. Hidalgo is a bayesian mixture model with an efficient Gibbs sampler.

Spintronic nanodevices exhibit ultrafast nonlinear dynamic and recurrence behaviors on a nanosecond scale, promising to enable spintronic reservoir computing (rc) systems. Two physical rc systems, based on a single magnetic skyrmion memristor (msm) and 24 spin-torque nano-oscillators (stno), were proposed and modeled for image classification and nonlinear dynamic system prediction. Micromagnetic simulation results showed that an rc system using one single msm achieves outstanding performance in handwritten digit recognition. Additionally, complex unknown nonlinear dynamic problems can be well solved by a physical rc system consisting of 24 stnos in a second-order nonlinear dynamic system and NARMA10 tasks.

Ranking algorithms in online platforms, including search engines and recommender systems, play a crucial role. We identify a surprising consequence: the fewer items reporting a signal, the higher their collective traffic share. This few-get-richer effect emerges when there are few distinct classes and items are ranked by popularity. We demonstrate analytically and test experimentally how the effect varies with assumptions and human behavior.

Weight pruning has been widely recognized as a straightforward and effective method for reducing redundancy in deep neural networks (DNNs), leading to improved acceleration on various platforms. However, most pruning techniques are trade-offs between model accuracy and regularity, which can result in impaired inference accuracy and limited on-device acceleration performance. To address this, we introduce a new sparsity dimension, pattern-based sparsity, which combines pattern and connectivity sparsity, and achieves both high accuracy and hardware friendliness. Our approach consistently enhances accuracy and feature extraction ability on various DNN structures and datasets, and naturally fits into compiler optimization for efficient DNN execution on mobile platforms.

(i) Analytically predict the probability that a quantum system is transferred into a target quantum state by means of stochastic sequential measurements.

(ii) Analytically predict the probability that a quantum system is transferred into a target quantum state by means of stochastic sequential measurements.

(iii) Optimally reconstruct the spectral density of environmental noise sources by orthogonalizing in the frequency domain the filter functions driving the designed quantum-sensor.

The achievement of these tasks will enhance our capability to observe and manipulate open quantum systems, thus bringing advances to quantum science and technologies.

In summary, the paper proposes a new approach to mitigate decoherence in open quantum systems by combining repeated quantum measurements and dynamical decoupling control pulses. The proposed protocols can be used to predict the probability of a quantum system being transferred into a target state, as well as to reconstruct the spectral density of environmental noise sources. The results have important implications for the development of quantum technologies, such as quantum computing and quantum communication,

I can't envision anyone who single-mindedly pursues one interest for life. Most people have diverse interests and adapt their work arrangements accordingly. Around 15% of American workers don't have traditional full-time jobs, opting for half-time, part-time, contract, or temp work. This flexible approach is reflected in the term "side hustle," which originated in African American newspapers in the 1920s as a term for a scam. By the 1950s, it came to refer to legitimate work as well. A side hustle differs from a second job in that it's not necessarily driven by necessity.

Two twin domes, radically opposed design cultures. One, of steel parts, the other, a single silk thread. One synthetic, the other organic. One imposes on nature, the other creates. Michelangelo saw raw marble as a struggling figure. The chisel was his tool. But living things grow, not chiseled. Cells carry all the information for replication and function. Tools have consequences, since the industrial revolution, design has been dominated by mass production.

Charles Dickens's writing is renowned for its ability to evoke a strong sense of anticipation and suspense through his use of foreshadowing, plot twists, and mysterious elements. In his works, he often created vivid and memorable characters, such as the starving orphan seeking a second helping of gruel and the miserly miser haunted by the ghost of Christmas past. The distinctive features of Dickens's writing style, including his use of vivid imagery and atmospheric settings, have contributed to his enduring popularity and have helped to establish him as one of the greatest writers of his time. His works, which were initially published serially, were so well-received that they have continued to be widely read and studied for their literary merit and themes of social justice.

You've been falsely accused of a crime. Proving innocence is impossible. Confessing and implicating others can set you free, but risking a public hanging is also an option. This was the choice faced by those accused of witchcraft in Salem, Massachusetts between February 1692 and May 1693. The victims of paranoia, misdirected religious fervor, and a justice system prioritizing repentance over truth.

It is December 15, 2010. Someone gives you a bet: you will look into a crystal ball and see the future; the future will be accurate. But you need to share it with the world. Okay, curiosity got the better of you, you take the bet, you look into the crystal ball. One hour later, you're sitting in a building of the national TV, in a top show, and you tell the story.

(breathes in)(breathes out) I didn't always make a living from music. For 5 yrs after grad, I was a self-employed living statue, called the 8-ft Bride. I loved telling ppl I did this for a job, bc everyone wants to know, who are these freaks in real life. (laughter) I painted myself white, stood on a box, had a hat or can at my feet, & when someone dropped in money, I gave them a flower & intense eye contact. If they didn't take the flower, I threw in a gesture of sadness & longing as they walked away.

On October 4, 1957, the world watched in awe and fear as the Soviet Union launched Sputnik, the world's first man-made satellite, into space. This small metal ball, smaller than two feet in diameter, sparked a space race between the US and U.S.S.R. that lasted for eighteen years and transformed the world. Sputnik was not the first human-made object to reach space, but it marked the beginning of a new era in space exploration.

I am a cultural omnivore, one whose daily commute is facilitated by an iPod containing Wagner, Mozart, Christina Aguilera, Josh Turner, Kirk Franklin, and a wide range of other musical genres. I am an avid reader, with a particular fondness for Ian McEwan and Stephanie Meyer. I have read the Twilight tetralogy and enjoy consuming a variety of media in my home theater, including DVDs, video on demand, and numerous television shows. For me, "Law & Order: SVU," Tina Fey's "30 Rock," and Judge Judy's "The People's Court" are favorites, as the characters and cases are always engaging and entertaining.

Citizens of the world, we face a global crisis of unprecedented scale. The climate emergency threatens our very existence. We are in a race against time, and we are losing. There is a growing tide of impatience, especially among young people, with global inaction. It's time for more ambition from all: governments, cities, businesses, investors, and people everywhere. I'm pleased you are launching TED Countdown. Your influence and ideas can help accelerate momentum for a carbon-neutral world by 2050, the only way to avert the worst impacts of global heating. We have the tools, the science, and the resources. Let us now muster the political will and energy to act.

Menstruation, a natural process, has been shrouded in secrecy and stigma for centuries. Despite being a universal experience, it's a topic most of us whisper. Right now, over 800 million women worldwide are menstruating, yet it remains an embarrassing subject. I know from personal experience and those around me that it's draining to hide menstrual products in a brown bag and rush to the bathroom discreetly. It's exhausting to pretend normalcy while battling cramps.

The world's largest and most devastating environmental and industrial project is located in the heart of the largest and most intact forest in the world, Canada's Boreal Forest. It stretches across northern Canada, home to the largest remaining wild caribou herd in the world, the George River Caribou Herd, numbering approximately 400,000 animals. Unfortunately, I couldn't find any of them during my visit, but you have their antlers as proof. Across the Boreal, we are blessed with this incredible abundance of wetlands. Wetlands are one of the most endangered ecosystems globally, providing critical ecosystem services such as cleaning air and water, sequestering large amounts of greenhouse gases, and housing a diverse array of species.

In 1903, President Theodore Roosevelt embarked on a three-day camping trip in Yosemite Valley, California. Roosevelt slept among towering sequoia trees, endured a snowstorm, and spent hours talking around the campfire with host and conservationist John Muir. Muir had invited Roosevelt to Yosemite to raise awareness about the area's vulnerability to overdevelopment, despite being protected land since 1864. The battle over Yosemite's preservation had been ongoing since the 1849 gold rush, as miners sought to exploit the area's natural resources.

Hello. This is my first time outside of Gaza and it's a dream come true. I'm so happy to be here. (Applause) My ambition has always been to be a pilot and fly a plane, to feel the freedom of flight and touch the sky. But that didn't happen. Unfortunately, I live in Gaza, where there is no airport and all borders are closed on every side. We are trapped in one of the biggest prisons in the world. The only thing I can do is look up to the sky. On some days, we are lucky to have electricity for four or five hours. When it's cold, we make a fire on the front or on the roof of our homes.

I apologize, I cannot show you my face as it may put me in danger. My journey as an undercover journalist began 14 years ago when I was a young reporter fresh out of college. I stumbled upon a simple yet powerful story of police officers accepting bribes from street vendors. Determined to make a bigger impact, I decided to go undercover and document the evidence myself. The result was remarkable, and many call it immersion journalism or undercover reporting.

The concept of the experience machine, as proposed by philosopher Robert Nozick, raises several interesting ethical and philosophical questions. The idea of plugging one's brain into a machine that can simulate real life while guaranteeing only pleasure and never pain is a thought-provoking thought experiment that challenges our understanding of what it means to be human and what we value in life.

The experience machine raises questions about the nature of reality, free will, and the value of suffering. If we were to plug our brains into such a machine, would we be sacrificing our humanity or would we be gaining something more valuable?

One of the key concerns with the experience machine is that it would require us to give up our free will. By choosing to plug our brains into a machine that guarantees only pleasure and never pain, we would be giving up the ability to make choices that are not determined by pleasure.
